Ron,

I believe that .US was held as a place saver so that the naming used
in the ARPANET/DDN environment could comply with CCITT/ISO standards when
and if ISO naming standards are adopted on the ARPANET/DDN.  We asked that
it be reserved so that it would not be used by anyone for something other than
the country code required by ISO.  If the ISO standards are adopted it is my
understanding that US would become the topmost domain (after world or
universe or whatever as the root) and that .COM, .EDU, .MIL etc would be
followed by .US in the domain name.  Since ISO requires that there be
a country name I don't see how it could be otherwise.

I think the situation is somewhat analogous to U.S. mail addresses.  Unless
one is sending a letter outside of the country domain (be it electronic or
physical,) the country is understood to be the one in which the message/letter
originated and the destination is understood to be in the same country or
country domain as the originating message; consequently, no country domain
would be needed as one is implied.  If the message/letter is crossing country
boundaries then a country designator would be required.

I agree with you that, if someone wishes to register a country domain in
our (DDN/ARPANET) name service, it should comply with CCITT/ISO country
code abbreviations to (hopefully) avoid problems later.

Jake Feinler/NIC
